## JavaScript Advanced Concepts

## Event Delegation

### ðŸ“˜ Definition
Event Delegation is a technique where you attach a single event listener to a parent element instead of multiple child elements.

### ðŸ’¡ How It Works
Events in JavaScript **bubble up** the DOM â€” from the target element to its ancestors.  
So, you can listen for an event on the parent and handle it based on the event target.

### ðŸ§  Example
```html
<ul id="list">
  <li>Item 1</li>
  <li>Item 2</li>
  <li>Item 3</li>
</ul>

<script>
document.querySelector("#list").addEventListener("click", (e) => {
  if (e.target.tagName === "LI") {
    console.log("Clicked item:", e.target.textContent);
  }
});
</script>
````

### âœ… Benefits

* Improves performance
* Reduces memory usage
* Handles dynamically added elements easily

---

## Debouncing & Throttling

### ðŸ§© Debouncing

Debouncing ensures that a function runs **only after a delay** since the last call.

#### Example

```js
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timer;
  return function (...args) {
    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}

const handleInput = debounce(() => console.log("Input typed"), 500);
window.addEventListener("keyup", handleInput);
```

### âš™ï¸ Throttling

Throttling ensures a function runs **at most once every X milliseconds**.

#### Example

```js
function throttle(func, limit) {
  let inThrottle;
  return function (...args) {
    if (!inThrottle) {
      func.apply(this, args);
      inThrottle = true;
      setTimeout(() => (inThrottle = false), limit);
    }
  };
}

window.addEventListener("scroll", throttle(() => console.log("Scroll event"), 1000));
```

### âœ… Use Cases

* Search input boxes (Debounce)
* Scroll or resize events (Throttle)

---

## Closures & Currying

### ðŸ”¹ Closure

A closure gives access to an outer function's scope from an inner function, even after the outer function has executed.

#### Example

```js
function outer() {
  let count = 0;
  return function inner() {
    count++;
    console.log(count);
  };
}

const counter = outer();
counter(); // 1
counter(); // 2
```

### ðŸ§  Why Use Closures?

* Data privacy
* Stateful functions
* Used in modules, event handlers

### ðŸ”¸ Currying

Currying transforms a function with multiple arguments into a sequence of functions taking one argument at a time.

#### Example

```js
function add(a) {
  return function (b) {
    return function (c) {
      return a + b + c;
    };
  };
}

console.log(add(1)(2)(3)); // 6
```

### âœ… Benefits

* Code reusability
* Functional programming style
* Easy partial application

---

## Iterators & Generators

### ðŸ”¹ Iterator

An iterator is an object that allows sequential access to elements of a collection.

#### Example

```js
const arr = [10, 20, 30];
const iterator = arr[Symbol.iterator]();

console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: 10, done: false }
console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: 20, done: false }
console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: 30, done: false }
console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: undefined, done: true }
```

### ðŸ”¸ Generator

A generator is a function that can be paused and resumed using `yield` and `next()`.

#### Example

```js
function* numberGenerator() {
  yield 1;
  yield 2;
  yield 3;
}

const gen = numberGenerator();
console.log(gen.next().value); // 1
console.log(gen.next().value); // 2
console.log(gen.next().value); // 3
```

### âœ… Benefits

* Efficient data streaming
* Lazy evaluation
* Async flow management

---

## Proxy & Reflect

### ðŸ”¹ Proxy

A Proxy lets you intercept and redefine fundamental operations (like reading, writing, or deleting properties).

#### Example

```js
const user = { name: "Anurag" };

const proxy = new Proxy(user, {
  get(target, prop) {
    console.log(`Getting ${prop}`);
    return target[prop];
  },
  set(target, prop, value) {
    console.log(`Setting ${prop} = ${value}`);
    target[prop] = value;
  },
});

proxy.name; // Getting name
proxy.age = 22; // Setting age = 22
```

### ðŸ”¸ Reflect

`Reflect` provides methods for object manipulation (mirrors object behavior).

#### Example

```js
const person = { name: "Anurag" };
Reflect.set(person, "age", 22);
console.log(Reflect.get(person, "age")); // 22
```

### âœ… Use Cases

* Validation
* Logging
* Access control
* Framework internals (like Vue, MobX)

